// Semantic direction:
// lineær_logikk is a resource-sensitive logic where propositions represent consumable resources.
// ll_strukturelle_regler: linear logic removes weakening and contraction — resources must be used exactly once.
// ll_tensor A⊗B: both A and B are available, and both must be consumed.
// ll_par A⅋B: the dual of tensor — used in the conclusion of linear sequent proofs.
// ll_med A&B: choose one of A or B (additive conjunction — like offering a choice).
// ll_pluss A⊕B: one of A or B is present (additive disjunction).
// ll_selvfølgelig !A marks an unlimited resource — can be copied, weakened, and used many times.
// bang_formel allows contraction (copy) and weakening (discard) only for !-marked propositions.
// ll_lollipop A⊸B: a linear function that consumes one A and produces one B.
// ressurs_splitting: Γ,Δ ⊢ t : A means t uses resources in Γ; Γ and Δ are disjoint.
// capability_splitting divides a capability between two uses without copying it.
// lineær_capability models file handles, network connections, and memory pointers safely.
// sessions_typer_fra_ll: session types arise from a Curry-Howard correspondence with linear logic.
// dual_type: the type !A must be the server end when !Ā is the client end.
// send_ll: !A⊗S means produce an A-value and continue with session S.
// propositions_as_sessions maps linear propositions directly to session type specifications.
// deadlock_frihet_ll: programs typed in the sessions_typer_fra_ll fragment are deadlock-free by construction.

// Primitive flow:
// Ressursforbruk: f : A⊸B og x : A
//   f x : B -- x er forbrukt, kan ikke brukes igjen
// Kopiering med !: g : !A⊸(A⊗A) -- ! tillater kopiering
//   g(!x) = (x, x) -- lovlig fordi x er !-merket
// Splitting: fn parallell(kilde: Nett⊸(Data⊗Nett))
//   la (data, nett2) = kilde(nett)  -- nett delt lineært
//   -- nett kan ikke brukes etter dette punktet
// Session type: type Protokoll = Motta[Int] ⊗ Send[Tekst] ⊗ End
//   handler: fn serve(k: Protokoll): { la (n, k2) = recv(k); send(k2, vis(n)) }

// This defines linear logic: tensor/par/with/plus/bang connectives, resource splitting,
// cut elimination, linear types with capability splitting, the Curry-Howard correspondence
// giving session types from linear propositions, deadlock freedom, and race freedom.
